{
  "texts": [
    "However, many interesting problems, such as physical control tasks, have continuous (real-valued) and high-dimensional action spaces (A = R N).",
    "In these cases, for the DQN to find the action that maximizes the Q-value estimate, an iterative optimization process would be necessary at each step of the agent.",
    "Therefore, Lillicrap et al. (2016) have based on the Deterministic Policy Gradient (DPG) algorithm (Silver et al. 2014) and the DQN to propose an actor-critic and model-free algorithm called Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient (DDPG) that uses deep neural networks with ER and can learn over continuous action spaces.",
    "According to the authors, DDPG can find policies whose performance is competitive (sometimes better) with those found by a planning algorithm with full access to the dynamics of challenging physical control problems that involve complex multi-joint movements, cartesian coordinates, unstable and rich contact dynamics, and gait behavior.",
    "They have evaluated their agent in learning action policies from video-frame pixels and physical control data (such as joint angles), using the same hyperparameters and network architecture in different challenges in simulated physical environments through a physics engine originally proposed for model-based control called MuJoCo (Todorov et al. 2012)."
  ]
}